ASCdiagSpec: When I was a sophmore in college I got a psych educational eval.I had been having issues for a long time and the therapist I was seeing at the time said I had symptoms of autism and adhd. My brother was diagnosed with autism very young and my dad has adhd. So I get a referal to clinic that tests and treats people with learning disorders. My offical diagnosis is nonverbal learning disorder, dyslexia, and innatientive adhd. That doctor who did the testing was odd. When she gave me my diagnosis she straight up told me that she was surprised I had never attempted suicide, and that I was the strangest case she had seen in 10 years. She also said it was different than autism, and then said I wasn't autistic because I wasn't flapping during all our appointments. This is to say she did try to tell me I am not on the spectrum, but she didn't seem to respect autistic people. It was a very weird expierence, it was nice that I could get help. Though my doctor treated me like if I showed the wrong symptoms I wouldn't be human to her anymore. (Also I asked my autistic brother about if he thought I had autism and he just laughed, and said he has for as long as he could remeber.) Also nonverbal learning disorder was a weird diagnosis to get, because it isn't in the DSM and my doctor said it is basicaly the replacement for the aspbergers lable. So, it is unclear if I am offically diagnosed as on the spectrum or not. It was a difficult process to get tested for learning disorders as an adult.

ASCdiagSpec: Being diagnosed with autisim is an important part of understanding yourself and your unique way of experiencing the world. Since I was clinically diagnosed at Med-Forum Hospital in Pretoria, it highlights that the diagnosis was conducted by professionals, through comprehensive evaluations such as interviews, observations, and standardized assessments.  Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) is a neurological and developmental condition that affects how a person communicates, interacts socially, and processes sensory information.
